pawn() and forms the basis for all other spawn variants:\n- Validates file parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck (line 540)\n- Validates entire args array with validateArgumentsNullCheck (line 556)\n- Validates optional shell parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck (line 613)\n- Validates argv0 option with validateArgumentNullCheck (line 597) if provided\n- Iterates through environment variable key-value pairs and validates both key and value for null bytes (lines 691-692)\n- Constructs envPairs array with validated environment variables\n- Returns normalized options object ready for C++ processing\n\n## Internal ChildProcess Class (lib/internal/child_process.js)\n\nThe **ChildProcess class** (lines 254-311) is the JavaScript wrapper that:\n- Extends EventEmitter for event-driven process lifecycle management\n- Initializes with a native C++ Process handle: this._handle = new Process() (line 266)\n- Implements spawn() method (lines 354-479) that:\n  - Receives pre-validated options from normalizeSpawnArguments()\n  - Calls this._handle.spawn(options) to invoke the C++ ProcessWrap.spawn()\n  - Sets up stdio streams for stdin, stdout, stderr (lines 462-467)\n  - Establishes IPC channel if needed (line 476)\n- Implements kill() method (lines 492-517) for process termination\n- Handles process exit events and error propagation\n\n## C++ Native Binding Layer\n\n### ProcessWrap Class (src/process_wrap.cc, lines 51-346)\n\nThe **ProcessWrap** class is the critical C++ bridge that:\n- Inherits from HandleWrap for libuv integration\n- Exposes Spawn() static method (lines 153-310) which:\n  - Receives validated options object from JavaScript\n  - Extracts file path (line 196): node::Utf8Value file(env->isolate(), file_v)\n  - Extracts and validates arguments (lines 209-225), allocating char** for argv\n  - Extracts and validates environment pairs (lines 237-251), allocating char** for env\n  - Parses stdio configuration via ParseStdioOptions() (line 254)\n  - Calls uv_spawn() (line 286) with the libuv process options\n  - Frees allocated memory for argv and env arrays (lines 297-305)\n  - Returns error code to JavaScript layer\n- Exposes Kill() method (lines 312-325) for sending signals to spawned processes\n- Registers callbacks for process exit events (OnExit, lines 327-343)\n\n### SyncProcessRunner (src/spawn_sync.h and src/spawn_sync.cc)\n\nHandles **synchronous spawning** (spawnSync/execFileSync/execSync) with:\n- CopyJsString() and CopyJsStringArray() methods for safe memory management\n- ParseOptions() method for input validation of synchronous spawn options\n- SyncProcessStdioPipe class for capturing stdout/stderr without blocking\n- Full event loop management within synchronous operation\n\n## Attack Prevention Design\n\nThe null-byte validation chain prevents command injection:\n\n1. **JavaScript Layer Prevention**: normalizeSpawnArguments() and related functions check all inputs for null bytes before passing to C++. This prevents attackers from using null bytes to truncate commands:\n   - Example blocked: spawn('sh', ['-c', 'echo foo\\0; malicious_command'])\n   - The \\0 would be detected and rejected at line 964\n\n2. **Comprehensive Coverage**: Every command component is validated:\n   - The executable file path cannot contain null bytes\n   - All argument array elements cannot contain null bytes\n   - Shell path cannot contain null bytes\n   - Environment variable names and values cannot contain null bytes\n\n3. **C++ Processing**: The ProcessWrap.spawn() method receives only already-validated data, making additional C++ validation unnecessary. The validated strings are passed directly to uv_spawn() without further inspection.\n\n4. **Protection Against OS-Level Tricks**: By rejecting null bytes at the JavaScript level, even if a developer accidentally or maliciously tries to pass null-byte-containing strings, the Node.js layer blocks them before they reach the OS, preventing:\n   - Command truncation attacks\n   - Argument injection via null-byte termination\n   - Environment variable injection\n\nThis design exemplifies defense-in-depth: input validation at entry points prevents malicious data from progressing to lower layers where it could be exploited."
